Bug ID: 50
Project: Closure
Bug Type: Semantic Fault (SF)

Step-by-step Bug Description:

1) The bug exists in the function named "tryFoldArrayJoin". This function is used for manipulating nodes, which seem to be part of an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) which represents the structure of source code in a language-agnostic way.

2) Test case failure caused by the bug was captured in the error message "junit.framework.AssertionFailedError:", indicating that an assertion in the test did not match the expected results.

3) The bug was located in the section of the code handling 'right', which is the next child of the call target node: 

```
Node right = callTarget.getNext();
if (right != null) {
    if (!NodeUtil.isImmutableValue(right)) {
        return n;
    }
}
```

In the above code, the function was only checking if 'right' was an immutable value, but it does not consider a situation where 'right' may have a next sibling. In other words, it doesn't handle the case where 'right' would have more than one value.

4) The correction was done by adding a condition to check if 'right' has a next sibling too. 

  ```
  Node right = callTarget.getNext();
  if (right != null) {
      if (right.getNext() != null || !NodeUtil.isImmutableValue(right)) {
           return n;
      }
  }
  ```

This ensures that the 'right' node can only contain one value, as the function is not prepared to handle multiple. 

5) Additionally, the fixed code checks if the 'right' node is a string and equals ",". If it does, it removes the child 'right' from the node 'n'. 

```
if (right != null && right.getType() == Token.STRING
    && ",".equals(right.getString())) {
  // "," is the default, it doesn't need to be explicit
  // remove child is called here
  n.removeChild(right);
  reportCodeChange();
}
```

This provides a remedy for scenarios where the explicit specification of a string as "," was not required as it's the default join string value. That makes the logic of the code aligned with the way JavaScript array join operation handles this situation. This additional fix is refining the semantics of the function based on the interpretation of the operation it seeks to emulate.

This contrast between the buggy code and correct code illustrates how not fully considering all properties of nodes in an AST can result in faulty functionality. A check was missing for the multiplicity of 'right' and specific use case of 'right' being exactly equal to ','.
